Growing up Mexican American is a hard world to navigate. In my adult life I’ve chosen to reconnect with a part of myself that was lost as a young child in assimilation. I’ve found that with these opportunities to travel to my ancestral lands (San Luis Potosí, Sinaloa) I’ve been able to find a part of myself that was missing. Through travel, food, storytelling and music we can reconnect with our heritage despite the language barriers that some of us may have. There are so many beautiful ways to connect with our family and culture 💗

What to do in Mazatlan, Sinaloa
What to do:

1. Isla Venado 
-Get a ride over with @mazatlankayakclub 
- water is calm and perfect for swimming 
-Small island take your own food and drink 
-Leave no trash 

2. Isla de la Piedra
-Go to the Nuevo embarcadero on bus, taxi or pulmonía and cross on boat taxi 
- Tons of restaurants to chose from but my family enjoys going to Puesta del Sol or Playa Azul 
- ride the banana boat or swim in the water 
- walk along the beach for amazing views and miles of palm trees 

3. Go out dancing 
-Mazatlan is known for its nightlife 
-Oyster is a classic and it’s right on the beach 

4. Visit centro histórico 
- walk around the architecture is absolutely stunning 
- visit mercado 
- olas altas 
-plaza machado 
- catedral if your into that stuff haha I go for the ice cream behind it

We get so focused on the interior that we forget sometimes about the 15 acres of raw beautiful desert landscape that surrounds the house.

Prepare and eat a meal outdoors, have a drink by the pool, gather at one of the fire pits or just sit on one of the hills and watch the sunset. There is so much to do this time of year outside in the desert. 

Thanks Lauren, btw make sure you check out her travel content, hope to see you again soon.

Falling back in love with the place I call home
When I was a little girl my abuelitos would take off on these grand road trips. They would arrive home several  months later and tell us all about where they had been
perfect little escape before the holidays

Pfeiffer Wedge Cabin
sleeps 4 comfortably 
1 full bed and a bunk bed with a little cushion mattress
* we put air mattresses on all 3 beds and they fit. 

Tips: Bring a broom to sweep cabin floor and a good sleeping bag with extra blankets because it gets chilly. String some lights or bring a good lamp it gets really dark beneath the trees. There’s no electricity however there are outlets near the bathrooms if you need to charge anything. There is firewood for sale as you pull into the park for $12 a bundle
